1. Problem statement¶

The following report is to explore the relationship between our dependent variable(median house values) with other variables. Eventually, this will help us understand how well these factors can predict the housing prices. In detail, we are going to see how median income, population & number of households impact *median house value*¶

3.3 Description of Variables:¶

- Dependent variable¶

median_house_value: The median value of houses in a given area, appended as dependent variable in our analysis.¶

- Independent variable¶

median_income: The median income of a given area, which we are trying to predict. Witnessed a strong correlation with housing prices.¶

population: The population represents the total number of residents in a given area, also as independent variable. However, the resultant impact on house values varies as inflation does't correlates with amplifying house property prices.¶

households: Households indicates the total count of households also as an independent variable which is potentially influenced by housing values.¶

Filter out records with median_house_value = 500001 since it seems to be a cap for the median_house_value.¶

4. Creating a Model for univariate linear regression¶

Created 3 models with respect to dependent variable median_house_value¶

Train the Model¶

1. median_house_value vs. median_income¶

2. median_house_value vs. population¶

3. median_house_value vs. housholds¶

Table¶

Creating a table to store all the¶
1. Slope¶
2. Intercept¶
3. Mean Squared Error¶
4. Mean Absolute Error¶
In [40]:
if "median_income" in train.columns and "population" in train.columns and "households" in train.columns:
    results = {
    "Model":[],
    "Intercept":[],
    "Slope":[],
    "mean_squared_error":[],
    "mean_absolute_error":[]
    }


    model_income = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    model_income.fit(train[["median_income"]], train[["median_house_value"]])

    y_predict_income = model_income.predict(train[["median_income"]])
    results["Model"].append("Median House Value vs Median Income")
    results["Intercept"].append(model_income.intercept_)
    results["Slope"].append(model_income.coef_)
    results["mean_squared_error"].append(mean_squared_error(train["median_house_value"], y_predict_income))
    results["mean_absolute_error"].append(mean_absolute_error(train["median_house_value"], y_predict_income))


    model_population = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    model_population.fit(train[["population"]], train[["median_house_value"]])

    y_predict_population = model_population.predict(train[["population"]])
    results["Model"].append("Median House Value vs Population")
    results["Intercept"].append(model_population.intercept_)
    results["Slope"].append(model_population.coef_)
    results["mean_squared_error"].append(mean_squared_error(train["median_house_value"], y_predict_population))
    results["mean_absolute_error"].append(mean_absolute_error(train["median_house_value"], y_predict_population))

    model_households = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    model_households.fit(X=train[["households"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])

    y_predict_households = model_households.predict(train[["households"]])
    results["Model"].append("Median House Value vs Households")
    results["Intercept"].append(model_households.intercept_)
    results["Slope"].append(model_households.coef_)
    results["mean_squared_error"].append(mean_squared_error(train["median_house_value"], y_predict_households))
    results["mean_absolute_error"].append(mean_absolute_error(train["median_house_value"], y_predict_households))

    results_Df = pd.DataFrame(results)

    print(results_Df)
    
else:
    print("Required columns are missing in training data")

Conclusion¶

Best model considered out of 3 above models was median_house_value vs. median_income. Outstanding features out of other models are as follows:¶
- Has lowest Mean Squared Error and Mean Absolute Error meaning better variance and less sensitive to outliers.¶
- Coefficient(Slope) is 38702.97 suggest strongest relationship of significant elevation between two variables¶

Additional insights¶

Further features including house_median_age, longitude, latitude and other house related constraints could enhance our predictions which ultimately helps in better accuracy.¶
